[3] Philippines (Davao city, Mindanao)
Date: Wed 5 Dec 2018
Source: SunStar Davao [abridged, edited]
https://www.sunstar.com.ph/article/1777302/Davao/Local-News/Report-Measles-kills-22-in-Davao-City


The Davao City Epidemiological Surveillance Unit (Davao CESU) recorded 22 measles deaths from January to September 2018.

In the data from CESU, there are 602 suspected cases of measles in the city from January to September 2018 and 45 of those are confirmed cases.

District C consisting of [10] barangays [smallest administrative division] has 83 suspected measles cases and 5 deaths, the highest so far in the city.

The data prompted the city government of Davao to intensify vaccination and immunization to children through the School-based immunization of the City Health Office (CHO) last August 2018; however, the CHO has low turnout as parents continue to fear Dengvaxia [vaccine for dengue fever].

"Measles (vaccine) has been given for decades with no complications and dengvaxia is new, we are not giving it [to the public]," CHO head Dr Josephine Villafuerte said on a text message to SunStar Davao on [Tue 4 Dec 2018].

Chief Technical Division of the CHO Doctor Julinda Acosta said yesterday [4 Dec 2018] the school-based immunization program continued to have a low turnout and this has become a problem.

"Ang measles ay hindi pa nawawala," [measles has not disappeared yet] she said, adding that their office may have to give the vaccines to private schools to be used since parents from public schools refuse to have their children immunized and vaccinated.

The World Health Organization (WHO) reported over 17 200 measles cases in the Philippines in 2018 or 367 percent increase compared to last year [2017].


[Byline: Lyka Amethyst H Casamayor]

